  "prompt": "When and how did WWI start and end?",
  "response": "World War I, also known as the Great War, started on July 28, 1914, and ended on November 11, 1918.\n\n### Start of World War I:\n1. **Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand**: The immediate catalyst for the war was the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary and his wife, Sophie, by Gavrilo Princip, a Bosnian Serb nationalist, on June 28, 1914, in Sarajevo. This event set off a chain reaction among the European powers.\n\n2. **July Crisis**: Following the assassination, a series of diplomatic and military maneuvers known as the July Crisis unfolded. Austria-Hungary, with the backing of Germany, issued an ultimatum to Serbia with demands that were intentionally unacceptable. When Serbia's response failed to satisfy all the demands, Austria-Hungary declared war on Serbia on July 28, 1914.\n\n3. **Alliance Systems**: The conflict quickly expanded due to existing alliances and treaties. Russia began mobilizing to support Serbia. Germany declared war on Russia on August 1, 1914, and then declared war on Russia's ally, France, on August 3, 1914. Germany's invasion of Belgium brought the United Kingdom into the war on August 4, 1914, due to its treaty obligations to defend Belgium.\n\n### End of World War I:\n1. **Armistice of November 11, 1918**: After four grueling years of trench warfare and significant loss of life, the war effectively ended with an armistice on November 11, 1918. The armistice was signed in a railway carriage in Compi\u00e8gne, France, and came into effect at 11 a.m.\u2014the eleventh hour of the eleventh day of the eleventh month.\n\n2. **Treaty of Versailles**: The formal end of the war came with the signing of the Treaty of Versailles on June 28, 1919. This treaty imposed heavy reparations and territorial losses on Germany and redrew the map of Europe in significant ways. The treaty is often cited as a contributing factor to the economic and political instability that led to World War II.\n\nThe aftermath of World War I saw vast political changes, including the collapse of empires such as the Austro-Hungarian, Ottoman, Russian, and German Empires, and set the stage for major geopolitical shifts in the 20th century.",
